    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should a Brisbane seller consider before agreeing to extra buyer access after unconditional?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Consider three things. First, what is the visit actually for, because a quick measure-up is very different from a half-day visit with three trades. Second, what is your insurance position, because uninvited contractors on your property can create a liability gap if someone is injured. Third, what could the visit surface that creates a new dispute, because allowing access to areas the buyer has not previously inspected can occasionally raise complaints about condition. Most reasonable requests are fine to accommodate with conditions attached."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can extra access between unconditional and settlement create new legal risk for a Brisbane seller?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. The seller remains responsible for the condition of the property until settlement. If a contractor attending on the buyer's behalf causes damage, the seller has to deal with the insurance and repair process before settlement, which can complicate the settlement timeline. Allowing access also creates a paper trail that the buyer may rely on to argue a condition has changed. The risks are manageable but a seller should think about them before saying yes, and should put conditions in writing through the agent or solicitor."
      }
    }
  ]
